Author: @hoangluu6943
Comment:
A lot of questions are about the safety and quality of information regarding vaccine and research in medicine.

This is because not many people are educated in the sciences that require laboratory work and experiments, as well as research papers that are graded heavily on a universal format: theory/introduction, abstract, data, analysis, conclusion.

A lot of people are in pre-med studies but not many finished the entire curriculum. Many changed majors and studies and never even got to calculus-based physics and organic chemistry and biochemistry. Many even forgot how to write a research paper or do a research project that requires a long list of bibliography or references.

This is the problem. Undergraduate studies in pre-med were rigorous. Students are taught to only use peer-reviewed articles and journals. I think the 20 public members do not even know what is a peer-reviewed source. They do not know the scientific methods -- what is research, what is a research writing format vs. a literary work or media source, what is a hypothesis vs. theory, how long or what does it take for a hypothesis to become a theory, etc.

People need to know that a discovered idea in science relating to causation that is supported with evidence, data and math, is not to be debated. It becomes a discovery, an idea, a lesson in our textbook because the experiment was done so many times and the results came back the same from so many schools and institutions throughout the country and around the world. It cannot be debated because it becomes a fact. This is how much it takes for a claim to be made that HIV leads to AIDS.

Science is rigorous, tedious, experimented, duplicated, data-proven, no/yes-claim but is math-claim or data-claim.

There is also a problem. The public does not have free access to a lot of medical and scientific journals that students have at their school. The public learn information from social media and the news. Unfortunately, we do not have a separate and widely circulated search engine for peer-reviewed sources for proven medicine and science. We just google everything :))

Author: @falahati
Comment:
An interesting mix of people to watch. To me, there were three kinds of people here, with some overlap:
1. Those who just wanted to be heard: they kept talking without waiting for answers. It felt like free speech, to them, meant freedom from judgment. With these people, you can often make progress by listening and guiding them to a clearer conclusion, rather than shutting them down.
2. Those with fixed beliefs: their conviction was almost religious, making it hard for them to see any benefit that conflicted with what they believed. These are the hardest to reach since you can’t take away someone’s “faith” easily.
3. Those with personal experiences: their concerns made sense, but the issue was a lack of understanding of statistics. With some explanation, they could see why vaccines are safe, even if they still never fully feel comfortable with them.

I especially appreciated how Dr. Mike skillfully navigated all three groups.

Author: @LIME_WATER
Comment: Vaccines are not 100% risk-free, but they are among the safest and most effective medical tools ever developed, preventing millions of deaths each year. In the 1980s, rising lawsuits against vaccine makers threatened to drive companies out of the market, which could have led to dangerous shortages. To protect public health while still supporting those who experience rare side effects, governments like the U.S. established the Vaccine Injury Compensation Program, which provides financial compensation funded by a small tax on each vaccine dose rather than through direct lawsuits. This system balances accountability with stability in vaccine supply. Vitamins and minerals, on the other hand, are regulated as dietary supplements, not mass-administered medical products, and while they can be harmful in high doses, they don’t play the same role in public health infrastructure and thus don’t require a similar liability framework.

His “study” only had 12 kids in it, and later investigations found he had flat-out falsified data.

On top of that, he had financial motives—he was being paid by lawyers who wanted to sue vaccine companies, and he was working on his own “rival” vaccines that would make him money if MMR got discredited.

The paper was fully retracted, and Wakefield lost his medical license for fraud and unethical conduct. Since then, dozens of massive studies with hundreds of thousands of kids have shown no connection between vaccines and autism.

But by that time, the misinformation had already spread, and that’s why people still believe it today.

Author: @irshaadsheikh7530
Comment:
It’s honestly a bit frightening how our brains are wired to believe that logical thinking and facts alone can solve every problem—when, in reality, the world is much messier. The irony is, people who are truly open-minded and knowledgeable recognize how much remains uncertain, while those who stubbornly cling to their beliefs often do so out of fear that new information might shatter their worldview. It’s not strength of conviction, but rather an unwillingness to question themselves.

True confidence isn’t about shutting out different perspectives, but about being able to update your own opinions as you learn. That’s the difference between stubbornness and real understanding.

Author: @Ubesoft-vc5te
Comment:
You're accusing him of blind belief? No. Everything he said — literally everything — was rooted in well-established, peer-reviewed medical knowledge. You know, the kind of knowledge that comes from decades of medical research, studies, trials, reviews — not from YouTube videos, echo chambers, or "my cousin had a bad reaction" stories. He was repeating what doctors, immunologists, and virologists have been saying for years. You call that blind belief? No — that’s called education.

Now let’s look at what the so-called "anti-vaxxers" brought to the table. A few had legitimate concerns, sure. That’s fair. But most of what was thrown out wasn’t proof — it was anecdotes, personal feelings, and internet conspiracy theories dressed up like evidence. Sorry, but personal emotion doesn't override global research. That’s not how debate works. That’s not how science works. And frankly, that’s not how medicine works.

So, since you’re so convinced he was blindly believing — I’ll challenge you directly. Show me one claim he made that wasn’t backed by actual medical research. Just one. Show me something he said that wasn’t echoed in medical textbooks, WHO briefings, CDC papers, or actual scientific literature. I guarantee you, I can show you exactly where that knowledge came from — and it won’t be from a podcast or a random blog.

Comment:
The doctor compared drunk driving to NOT getting a vaccine. This is like comparing a negative to a positive. -2 does not equal 2. Imagine your starting point is zero.. if you drink alcohol and become impaired and then drive a vehicle, you've actively done multiple negative things. You are negative. Now if this person had not put the toxin in the body and driven a vehicle then the risk would have been eliminated entirely. And the person would have remained at zero.
There would be zero chance they would have been harmed or harmed another person.
Now we move to the vaccine argument.
The assumption is that by NOT injecting a toxin, you could harm yourself and others.
The starting point is zero. Now the person getting a vaccine(pick your poison) who started at zero has now injected a toxic into the blood and immediately takes on a percentage of risk. The doctor agreed .. there is risk involved. So now you have to get into forcing risk to prevent risk.
The drunk driver takes on ZERO risk by not consuming the toxin.
The person forced(or willing) to take a vaccine has to immediately take on risk and put their faith in other humans to have their best interest in mind when clearly humans deceive other humans all the time, on both a large scale and individual scale.
At the very least, it's a poor and misleading comparison.

Author: @randomobssessions-y2i
Comment: Half of the people fighting against vaccines don’t even seem to know how vaccines actually work. Vaccines are in simple terms a way of giving your body a small “piece” of an illness so your body can’t develop a defense mechanism around that bacteria, so if you catch the illness your body already knows how to fight that disease since you have been exposed to a small part of the disease already with the vaccine. The vaccines builds a sort of protection, it’s kind of like training wheels so if you actually get the full illness (which in this analogy would be riding the bike) you already know how to fight it because you had the training wheels (aka the vaccine). The vaccine sets up your body to be able to fight the illness if you were to catch it. As the doctor says many times a vaccine acts as a PROTECTION. It is not an assured PREVENTION.

Author: @CarrotSensitive
Comment:
You're assuming the immune system is some perfect system that just turns on, does its job, and shuts off cleanly, but that’s not how it actually works. That’s where the risk comes in. You can’t really measure low-grade chronic inflammation (CRP barely scratches the surface to be honest), and that kind of simmering immune activity is extremely common if not a given in modern humans with constant insults, especially with stuff like neuroinflammation, metabolic issues, HPA axis dysregulation/ stress, poor redox status etc.
So if your immune system is already on edge and you throw a vaccine at it, which is basically poking it and saying “hey, react to this”....yeah, it might chase you out the door, but sometimes that chase doesn’t end. Once NF-kB, STAT3 and the other inflammatory pathways are switched on, they don’t always switch off easily and switch back to NRF2 etc. That’s the nuance people skip when they act like vaccines are just harmless little training sessions for your immune system. It’s not that simple.

Author: @alibahmani7801
Comment:
Since you're clearly missinformed let me tell you what's really in vaccines. Vaccines do not contain mercury they contain thimerosal. Thimerosal is a mercury-containing compound (approximately 49.6% mercury by weight).
It was used as a preservative to prevent contamination in multi-dose vials of vaccines.
It contains ethylmercury, which is broken down and cleared from the body more quickly than methylmercury (the type found in some fish and known to be more toxic).Most childhood vaccines are thimerosal-free or contain only trace amounts.
Since around 2001, thimerosal has been removed or reduced to trace levels in all routine childhood vaccines (e.g., MMR, polio, DTaP, Hib, Hepatitis B).
Still may contain thimerosal.
Some multi-dose flu vaccines (influenza) still use thimerosal.
However, single-dose flu vaccines are available without thimerosal.
No credible scientific evidence shows that thimerosal causes autism or other developmental disorders.
Multiple large studies and reviews by the CDC, WHO, and FDA have confirmed its safety at the levels used in vaccines.
I hope that clears up your missconceptions and hopefully you'll stop spreading missinformation to further whatever your cause is and use facts instead.

Author: @BigNoseEnergy
Comment:
Yes, Kary Mullis invented PCR and won the Nobel Prize, but his views on HIV and AIDS were highly controversial and not supported by the scientific community. Despite his achievements, Mullis denied the link between HIV and AIDS, a position that has been thoroughly discredited and widely criticized by experts and researchers worldwide. The overwhelming scientific consensus, backed by decades of evidence, is that HIV does cause AIDS. Citing Mullis to refute this is misleading and ignores the massive body of research that proves otherwise.

It's like if a brilliant car engineer who invented a revolutionary engine later claimed that seat belts don’t save lives. Just because they’re an expert in one area doesn’t make their opinion correct in another, especially when decades of safety data say otherwise. In the same way, Mullis’s invention of PCR doesn’t validate his personal beliefs about HIV, which contradict extensive scientific evidence.

Author: @BigNoseEnergy
Comment:
It’s important to focus on the facts rather than assumptions about motives or who was chosen for the conversation. The video showed a doctor calmly addressing common misinformation — and the goal was to clarify science, not stage a “lecture.”

The idea that there’s some global conspiracy using pandemics to profit or control populations is a serious claim but doesn’t stand up to evidence. Vaccines have saved millions of lives worldwide and are developed and distributed by countless scientists and health professionals working independently across many countries.

As for the comment section, online spaces can attract all kinds of opinions — including bots and trolls — but that doesn’t change the overwhelming scientific consensus or the real-world benefits of vaccination.

Author: @BigNoseEnergy
Comment:
I get the frustration with feeling like education can be influenced by funding, but the truth is that scientific knowledge isn’t just “mantras” learned blindly—it’s built through rigorous research, peer review, and reproducible evidence over decades. Doctors and scientists are trained to question, test, and update what they know based on data, not just repeat what they were taught.

On the other hand, anecdotal evidence from 20 people, while personally meaningful, doesn’t hold the same weight as large-scale studies involving thousands or millions of people. Personal stories can be powerful, but they can’t replace objective scientific methods that help us understand how vaccines work and their safety.

Regarding experts debating both sides—science thrives on open discussion, but it’s important the “experts” on both sides are qualified and base their arguments on credible evidence. Too often, so-called “experts” opposing vaccines rely on misinformation or discredited claims, which doesn’t make for a fair or productive debate.

The best approach is to listen to qualified professionals who base their conclusions on the full body of evidence, rather than isolated anecdotes or conspiracy theories.

It’s true that vaccines have become a routine part of healthcare, and sometimes it feels like they’re just taken for granted. But the reality is that most vaccines we use today have been developed because they prevent serious, sometimes deadly diseases. The goal has always been to protect public health, not just profit.

Author: @BigNoseEnergy
Comment: nstead of suing manufacturers directly, individuals who believe they’ve been injured by a vaccine can file a claim through the National Vaccine Injury Compensation Program (VICP). This program provides compensation for rare vaccine-related injuries and is funded by a small tax on vaccines. If a claim through the VICP is denied or the individual is unsatisfied with the compensation, they still have the option to pursue a lawsuit against the vaccine manufacturer in civil court, but only under very limited circumstances. These cases are rare and typically require proving that the manufacturer was negligent or that the vaccine was defective in some way. The system is designed to balance protecting vaccine manufacturers to encourage vaccine development while still offering a pathway for people to seek justice if they suffer harm. However, most vaccine injury claims are resolved through the VICP, which aims to provide faster and more accessible compensation than traditional lawsuits.

Actually, mRNA vaccines are vaccines. They work by teaching your cells how to make a harmless piece of the virus’s spike protein, which then triggers your immune system to recognize and fight the real virus if you’re exposed.

This is just a new type of vaccine technology, different from traditional ones that use weakened or inactivated viruses. But the goal is the same: to train your immune system to protect you from disease.

So, mRNA vaccines fit the definition of vaccines—they help your body prepare to defend itself without causing illness.

Author: @kyriacosmenikou5175
Comment:
It’s true that autism spectrum disorder (ASD) diagnosis rates have risen significantly since the 1980s. However, this does not necessarily mean that actual autism prevalence has risen by the same margin. The increase is widely attributed to:
Broader diagnostic criteria:
The definition of autism has expanded since the 1990s to include milder forms (like Asperger’s, now under ASD).

In the 1980s, autism often meant only severe, non-verbal cases; today it includes a wider spectrum.

Increased awareness:
Parents, teachers, and clinicians are now more aware of early signs of autism and more likely to seek diagnosis.

Schools and healthcare providers screen for autism more proactively.

Better access to services:
Diagnosis opens access to educational and therapeutic resources, which encourages earlier detection.

Author: @srishti7313
Comment:
People don't understand that the reason their kids didn't get any diseases is because of herd immunity. You don't need 100% of the population to be vaccinated, just 80%. The reason their kids didn't get it was because the other children were all vaccinated. They didn't carry the pathogen with them, so that's why they didn't get it. Most of the people they interacted with were all vaccinated hence they never had a chance of getting these infections.

However, the point of vaccine causing a lot of side effects is still valid. Like the son saying his mom's face got half paralysed is honestly so sad. But that's also why proper testing needs to be done for these vaccines. I do agree that some companies may be money minded and not prioritise effective testing to save costs, and unfortunately that does happen. It's abt which companies make reliable vaccines, and which to trust.

I also feel like these people don't understand how vaccines work. They aren't just "chemicals injected into the body" they are the weakened / dead form of the pathogen that's injected so your body develops an immune response and makes those particular antibodies for it. And those antibodies can then be made again in case of another attack.

I do understand both the perspectives of vaccinations vs anti vaccinations, but I think if "no vaccinations" mindset becomes widespread, it may lead to extinct diseases coming back and causing more pandemics. Diseases like small pox, polio, etc.

There may be side effects, but vaccination is important to prevent the spread of diseases.

Author: @zoe0640
Comment: I had never heard about Gates' statement and had to research it, then talk to an expert. Gates referenced a correlation between better health outcomes and lower population growth that sounds absolutely like Opposite Land to an American. Or most Americans. In America, a family that lost a child to illness may actually be less likely to have more children. So we have a bias that more people surviving childhood equals greater population growth. And it does in the short term. But think back to your grandparents' and great-grandparents' families. How many siblings did they have? 8? 9? And how many of them survived childhood? And how many children were required as labor on their parents' farms, or expected to take care of their elderly parents, or sent off to work in the cities and send money home? There are areas of the globe that still rely on large families. And they have more children than they expect to see reach afulthood because of the horribly high probability some of those children won't grow up. Imagine in 2025 fully expecting some of your children won't see adulthood. It's heartbreaking. And Gates probably wasn't trying to sound clinical when he referenced the data that when families can reasonably expect their children to grow up, they can confidantly have fewer children. You can better predict the size of your family. Not with absolute certainty, but with the certainty of our families starting in the 50s and 60s when we saw the idea of 2.5 children emerge. Other cultural changes coincided (and there is an expectant coincidence of vaccines and education meaning fewer children due to ignorance, but we also had increased urbanization and other factors - including social security - which meant that children were less of an economic asset and more of an expense), and I can't swear that Gates' prediction would be true, but he was referencing a statistical trend that the less risk to life correlates to a shallower population growth. He also specifically did not reference reducing the existing population, but rather that birth rates overall would come down. Why was Gates advocating slowing population growth? Not as an end in itself. His talk was on factors relevant to carbon emissions and population was one of several factors. A lower population worldwide does equate to lower emissions.

Author: @itsokaynatalie
Comment: It think the format of this debate is inherently flawed. The person the group is debating often doesn’t have enough time to respond to their claims because they control when the conversation stops (by raising enough flags) and they also get to speak first and potentially run down the clock. A far more balanced format would allow for the person the group is debating to fully finish their reply even if the person gets tapped out or the clock runs out. In addition, maybe there could be some sort of structure to cap the group member’s initial comments to a certain time limit, so it’s not 70%-80% the group speaking and 20%-30% of the person they’re debating speaking.

Author: @ericalin5432
Comment:
Jubilee, as a former fan of your channel, and as a pharmacy school student: With public health topics like this, it’s absolutely essential to handle it with absolute care, as it can have devastating consequences if you give an unchecked platform to potentially harmful viewpoints. Your priority should always be to have educational, civil conversations - not in finding catchy, viral moments and novelty. This is counterproductive and adds to the division and polarization.

It’s unconstructive to have conversations cut off halfway, not allowing the expert to flesh out their stance and arguments, but giving plenty of air time to the individuals who carry all host of opinions. Conversations should also not be timed, but rather let dialogue flow at its natural pace. This might mean having only 1 or 2 contestants in the entire video, which is totally fine, and actually much preferred if it means better quality conversation. With a platform as large as yours, it’s important to yes, have difficult or controversial conversations, but ultimately even more important to show growth and learning and unity through the discourse that takes place. That is not what I’m seeing in the platform you have today, which is disappointing. I implore you to take this constructive feedback to heart - I believe your channel has and can continue to make a positive difference in the world ❤

Author: @tadferd4340
Comment:
​@@dsfmdiya7500The primary hypothesis for claims of spontaneous combustion is called the wicking effect. Basically if a corpse lights on fire, starting somewhere on the torso and not the limbs, the fats will provide fuel until the torso burns up. Some of the time, the fire fails to spread to the limbs due to poor fuel availability. This results is basically untouched limbs around a scorched section, which can be interpreted as the body just catching fire from no where, when in reality there was an external flame source.

TL;DR: Human bodies burn weird, and it can look like the body just burst into flames, when it didn't.

Just in case you were curious.

Author: @PratikDhonsa
Comment:
Vaccine: What Is It?

Definition: A vaccine is a medical treatment designed
to protect against certain diseases by stimulating the immune system to recognize and fight off pathogens (like bacteria or viruses).

How It Works: Vaccines introduce a small, harmless part of a virus (or bacteria) to the immune system, teaching it how to recognize and destroy the actual pathogen if it enters the body in the future.



---

The Truth About Vaccines:

Safety: Vaccines are rigorously tested for safety and effectiveness before being approved for use. Millions of doses are given worldwide, and the benefits far outweigh the risks.

Effectiveness: Vaccines have successfully eradicated diseases like smallpox, significantly reduced diseases like polio, and are preventing outbreaks of diseases like measles, mumps, and rubella.

Herd Immunity: When enough people are vaccinated, diseases cannot spread easily, protecting vulnerable groups who can't get vaccinated (e.g., babies, the elderly, or those with weakened immune systems).



---

Debunking False Information:

1. "Vaccines cause autism"

False: This claim originated from a fraudulent study in 1998, which was retracted and discredited. Extensive research since then has shown no link between vaccines and autism.



2. "Vaccines are not safe"

False: Vaccines are highly regulated and undergo years of testing. Side effects are rare, and when they occur, they are usually mild and short-lived.



3. "Natural immunity is better than vaccination"

False: While natural immunity can develop after contracting a disease, it's often accompanied by serious health risks (hospitalization, long-term effects, even death). Vaccines provide protection without the danger of severe illness.



4. "Vaccines are part of a government conspiracy"

False: This claim is part of an unfounded conspiracy theory. The goal of vaccination programs is public health, not control. Governments and health organizations work to prevent disease outbreaks, not to harm people.

Author: @kirschmichel147
Comment:
Not quite. Ofc HIV is the Virus that causes AIDS, but AIDS(=Aquired immune deficiancy synrome) is the end stage of an HIV infection which usually manifests years or decades after the initial infection. Under modern treatment, (nearly) no HIV infected patient develops AIDS anymore and even patients with already fully developed AIDS (which basically means having almost no functioning immune System at all anymore) can be brought back to a normal life with a functioning immune system.
But being infected with HIV means lifelong treatment no matter what, since the infection itself can't be cured. Just the symptoms and the ability to infect others can be controlled.
